The ARTISTICC project conducted a trans-disciplinary scientific inquiry into the challenges coastal communities face in developing and implementing scientifically robust, evidence-based policies for adapting to climate-driven environmental change. The project involved a collaboration of researchers based in France, Canada, Russia, Senegal, India, and the United States with communities in seven nations around the world. Coastal community study sites included three arctic communities ? Wainwright, Alaska, USA, Uummannaq, Greenland, and Tiksi, Russia ? two temperate sites ? Cocagne-Grande Digue, New Brunswick, Canada and Bay of Brest, France ? and two tropical sites ? Mbour District, Senegal and the South India coastal zone (see figure).

 Research objectives included:


Developing locally meaningful scenarios of change using available 	climate and impact science;


Understanding current adaptation pathways as they enable future 	adaption;


Linking memories of adaptation to past changes to current adaptation 	challenges;


Understanding adaptation as a multidimensional and multi-temporal 	concept for coastal communities;


Understanding the role of cultural mediation of science in fostering 	local action for coastal adaptation;


Scoping what elements of science-based elements communities actually 	use in designing local adaptation strategies;


Producing in partnership with study communities a set of policy 	briefs addressing the community-level challenges to the defining 	evidence-based coastal adaptation policies.
Research methods were largely qualitative, with data gathered from 	community focus groups and semi-structured interviews with residents 	A major finding that emerged from the research was the central role 	that local institutions, both informal and formal, played in 	adaptation pathways. Communities with strong local formal and 	informal institutions appeared to be better able to adapt to 	climate-driven environmental change and other co-occurring changes 	without community disruption or loss of well-being than communities 	where these institutions were weak. The best results appeared in 	communities where strong local institutions operated together with 	support and recognition by higher authorities. These findings align 	with results obtained from other studies, and contribute to the 	growing body of research that points to the importance of local 	institutions as a key element of adaptive capacity.




